{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523203"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13884"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13884"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.09,0.41,0.07,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107965"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6501"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13884"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2456"},{"type":"tags","id":"2457"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34098"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107965"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after being pulled unconscious from the water at a beach in southern Australia. Her friends report that she was snorkelling in shallow water when she suddenly began to have difficulty breathing and became paralysed within minutes. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears cyanotic with a respiratory rate of 6/min, heart rate of 100/min, blood pressure of 100/60 mmHg, and oxygen saturation of 85% on room air. She is unresponsive to verbal stimuli but opens her eyes to pain. She has generalised muscle weakness and is unable to move her limbs or speak. Pupils are fixed and dilated. Skin examination is unrevealing for obvious stings or welts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following aquatic animals is most likely responsible for this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Box jellyfish","Stonefish","Blue-ringed octopus","Cone snail","Irukandji jellyfish"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with envenomation by a \u003Cstrong\u003Eblue-ringed octopus\u003C/strong\u003E. These small octopuses, found in tide pools and coral reefs in the Pacific and Indian oceans, produce tetrodotoxin, a potent neurotoxin that causes rapid onset of paralysis and respiratory failure. The patient\u0027s symptoms of sudden respiratory distress, paralysis, and unresponsiveness within minutes of exposure are hallmark signs of blue-ringed octopus envenomation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Australia they are found in subtropical waters off eastern Australia, south of the Great Barrier Reef in southern Queensland, New South Wales, Victoria, Tasmania and South Australia. They are an important venomous marine animal in coastal communities and health services. Before a proper understanding of managing blue-ringed octopus envenomation there have been several reported deaths however with widespread knowledge of first aid management there have been limited reports of adverse outcomes recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe geographical location is also a crucial diagnostic clue. Blue-ringed octopuses are the only species on this list commonly found in the temperate waters of southern Australia. The other marine animals listed are predominantly found in tropical waters further north, making them less likely culprits in this southern Australian beach scenario. When considering marine envenomations, understanding the geographical distribution of dangerous species is essential for rapid diagnosis and appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBox jellyfish\u003C/strong\u003E stings can cause severe pain, cardiovascular collapse, and death, but they typically produce immediate, severe pain and visible welts on the skin, which are not described in this case. Box jellyfish are found in tropical waters of northern Australia, not in southern regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStonefish\u003C/strong\u003E envenomation causes intense localised pain but does not typically lead to systemic paralysis or respiratory failure. These fish are also more common in tropical and subtropical waters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECone snail\u003C/strong\u003E envenomation can cause paralysis, but it usually begins with localised numbness and pain at the sting site, progressing more slowly to generalised paralysis. The rapid onset in this case is more typical of blue-ringed octopus envenomation. Cone snails are found in tropical waters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrukandji jellyfish\u003C/strong\u003E stings typically cause severe generalised pain, sweating, nausea, and hypertension rather than the paralysis and respiratory failure seen in this patient. These jellyfish are found in tropical waters of northern Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment for blue-ringed octopus envenomation is primarily supportive, as there is no antidote. The patient will likely require intubation and mechanical ventilation until the effects of the toxin wear off, which can take several hours to days. Prompt recognition and respiratory support are crucial for survival.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Blue-ringed octopus envenomation causes rapid onset of paralysis and respiratory failure due to tetrodotoxin.","Supportive care, including mechanical ventilation, is the mainstay of treatment for blue-ringed octopus envenomation as there is no antidote.","Rapid recognition of blue-ringed octopus envenomation is crucial for prompt initiation of life-saving interventions."],"references":["Berling I, Isbister G. Marine envenomations. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2015;44:28-32. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/24a5a6bf-1eb6-4f50-b44b-2717c8f59b38/Marine-envenomations.aspx#:~:text=Patients%20presenting%20with%20Irukandji%2Dlike"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13884"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90378"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T12:16:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T12:16:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6501"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107965"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ